derivation.yuyuan_name: Old English gē, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch gij and German ihr

graphic variant; in late Middle English &th; (see thorn) came to be written identically with y, so that the could be written ye. This spelling (usually y&+{e) was kept as a convenient abbreviation in handwriting down to the 19th cent., and in printers' types during the 15th and 16th cents., but it was never pronounced as ‘ye’
